<html><head><title>JS fetch() over the wire</title></head><body>
<h1>fetch() live test</h1>
<p>This page's &lt;script&gt; calls the JavaScript <b>fetch()</b> builtin against a
second endpoint on the host HTTP server. On device the engine's fetch()
transport is wired to the kernel http9 client (Plan-9 /net; no sockets), so this
is a REAL over-the-wire request. The fetched body is printed to the JS console,
which hambrowse mirrors to the serial log as a guest marker.</p>
<script>
fetch("__FETCH_URL__").then(function (r) {
  return r.text().then(function (t) {
    console.log("HAMFETCH status=" + r.status + " ok=" + r.ok + " ct=" +
                r.headers.get("content-type") + " body=[" + t + "]");
  });
}).catch(function (e) {
  console.log("HAMFETCH ERROR " + (e && e.name) + " " + (e && e.message));
});
</script>
</body></html>
